In TypeScript, you can use a type assertion to tell the type system that you know a value will have a specific type, even if it may have multiple types in theory. A type assertion is a way of telling the type checker to ignore the actual type of a value and assume that it has the specified type.

For example, if you have a function that accepts a string or a number, but you know that in practice it will only accept a string, you can use a type assertion to tell the type checker to treat the value as a string:
```
function myFunction(value: string | number) {
  // value will always be treated as a string
  const strValue = value as string;
  console.log(strValue);
}
```
In this example, the variable `strValue` is declared as having the type `string`, even though its actual type may be `string | number`. This is because we are using a type assertion to tell the type checker that we know the value will always be treated as a string.

