Here is a simple C++ program that reads a text file line by line and counts the number of occurrences of a specific word in the file:

#include <iostream>
#include <fstream>
#include <string>
using namespace std;

int main() {
    string word;
    int count = 0;

    // Prompt user to enter the word to search for
    cout << "Enter the word to search for: ";
    getline(cin, word);

    // Open the file and read each line
    ifstream infile("filename.txt");
    string line;
    while (getline(infile, line)) {
        // Check if the current line contains the word
        if (line.find(word) != string::npos) {
            count++;
        }
    }

    // Print the number of occurrences of the word
    cout << "The word " << word << " occurs " << count << " times." << endl;

    return 0;
}

In this program, we use the ifstream class to open the text file and read each line. We use the getline function to read each line from the file into a string variable called "line". We then use the find function to check if the current line contains the word that we are searching for. If it does, we increment a counter variable called "count". Finally, after reading all lines in the file, we print out the number of occurrences of the word.

Note that you will need to replace "filename.txt" with the actual name of your text file.

